<i>their favorite smell,</i>

38:38.441 --> 38:39.525
<i>their favorite food,</i>

38:40.109 --> 38:41.485
<i>or their owner.</i>

38:52.038 --> 38:55.499
<i>And more than half the time,</i>
<i>they choose their people.</i>

38:56.959 --> 38:59.170
I think he loves you.

38:59.253 --> 39:01.881
<i>It seems the heart trumps the stomach.</i>

39:03.174 --> 39:06.552
<i>So is this proof that cats love us?</i>

39:06.635 --> 39:09.555
I get asked a lot
whether cats love us or not.

39:09.638 --> 39:14.352
Love is a really complex emotion,
and even in humans, you know,

39:14.852 --> 39:18.022
someone might tell you that they love you,
but they behave very differently.

39:20.858 --> 39:24.487
<i> To answer that question</i>
<i>and understand the true nature</i>

39:24.570 --> 39:26.197
<i>of the human-cat relationship,</i>

39:26.280 --> 39:28.824
<i>we need to go</i>
<i>all the way back to the beginning.</i>

39:34.330 --> 39:38.250
<i>For years, historians believed</i>
<i>our friendship began in Egypt</i>

39:38.334 --> 39:39.919
<i>around 4,000 years ago.</i>

39:43.047 --> 39:46.300
<i>But a recent breakthrough</i>
<i>changed everything.</i>

39:53.057 --> 39:54.767
Ten thousand years ago,

39:55.267 --> 39:58.729
so before the Neolithic,
there were no cats in Cyprus.

40:01.190 --> 40:04.527
<i> Cyprus is a small island</i>
<i>in the Mediterranean</i>

40:04.610 --> 40:06.737
<i>near the cradle of civilization</i>

40:06.821 --> 40:10.616
<i>where archaeologists</i>
<i>recently unearthed a huge discovery.</i>

40:12.284 --> 40:15.121
They found a Neolithic burial of a child.

40:15.204 --> 40:18.332
And in this burial,
there was also a cat skeleton.

40:19.917 --> 40:23.629
<i> Dr. Eva Maria used DNA</i>
<i>to date this find.</i>

40:24.755 --> 40:27.133
<i>And it would become</i>
<i>the earliest known evidence</i>

40:27.216 --> 40:29.385
<i>of a human-cat relationship…</i>

40:32.763 --> 40:36.934
<i>…proving we've been together</i>
<i>for at least 10,000 years.</i>

40:39.437 --> 40:41.939
This cat did not swim over the sea.

40:43.149 --> 40:48.237
It means that people took this cat
on their ships to Cyprus.

40:48.737 --> 40:52.700
So something happened
around this time in this area.

40:53.784 --> 40:55.703
<i>What happened was the farm.</i>

40:57.496 --> 41:00.624
<i>Humans began to grow crops</i>
<i>and store grains,</i>

41:00.708 --> 41:03.544
<i>and wildcats saw an opportunity.</i>

41:05.171 --> 41:08.549
These granaries
must have attracted rodents,

41:08.632 --> 41:11.177
which was a disaster
for the early farmers.

41:11.260 --> 41:13.095
And so the cats

41:14.388 --> 41:16.891
jumped on these rodents
and thrived on the rodents.

41:17.850 --> 41:21.187
And this was probably
the beginning of this relationship

41:21.270 --> 41:24.440
between the wildcats and humans.

41:25.441 --> 41:28.068
<i>And from here, the relationship grew.</i>

41:29.570 --> 41:31.322
Egyptians worship cats.

41:31.864 --> 41:34.700
You had millions of cats mummified,

41:34.783 --> 41:40.623
and from the Egyptian iconography,
statues, all kind of depictions of cats.

41:41.540 --> 41:46.545
And there you see chairs
of noble people, very often women,

41:47.379 --> 41:49.840
and a little cat under the chair.

41:51.342 --> 41:56.013
So this shows us
that the cat had entered the house.

41:56.639 --> 41:58.933
It was on the way to become a house cat.

42:00.142 --> 42:02.019
<i>Wherever we went, cats followed…</i>

42:04.230 --> 42:05.397
<i>often by boat.</i>

42:07.399 --> 42:10.027
Ships are probably

42:10.110 --> 42:14.114
the predominant means
of spreading of the cat.

42:15.074 --> 42:17.618
The rodents went on the ships,
and the cats followed.

42:17.701 --> 42:20.412
And so there was not
a single ship, probably,

42:20.496 --> 42:22.831
that went out of the port without cats.

42:23.332 --> 42:29.338
<i>So this is how </i>Felis catus
<i>made its way to every continent on Earth.</i>

42:33.384 --> 42:39.348
It was so important on ships
that until 1975 in the British Navy,

42:39.431 --> 42:42.726
it was still compulsory
to have a cat on the ship.

42:43.644 --> 42:45.396
<i> It wasn't just the British.</i>

42:50.651 --> 42:54.071
<i> Attention, Mr. Coast Guardsman.</i>
<i>Herman the cat is on the prowl.</i>

42:54.154 --> 42:57.992
<i>In Baltimore, Herman is fingerprinted,</i>
<i>or is it, uh, paw-printed,</i>

42:58.075 --> 43:00.494
<i>so he can get</i>
<i>an official Coast Guard pass.</i>

43:02.955 --> 43:04.373
<i> This is real.</i>

43:05.457 --> 43:09.336
<i>Herman the cat was actually</i>
<i>in the US Coast Guard.</i>

43:11.297 --> 43:15.509
<i>But history hasn't always been</i>
<i>this kind to felines.</i>

43:25.227 --> 43:27.813
<i>Stories of black cats and dark magic,</i>

43:28.397 --> 43:31.358
<i>witches and cauldrons</i>
<i>did not begin in Salem</i>

43:32.067 --> 43:33.652
<i>or even Transylvania</i>

43:34.570 --> 43:38.032
<i>but with a rogue pope named Gregory IX.</i>

43:39.825 --> 43:41.744
Cats in the Middle Ages

43:42.745 --> 43:44.663
were associated to witches.

43:45.331 --> 43:47.166
Witches were actually

43:48.125 --> 43:53.964
intelligent women,
wise women who knew a lot about nature.

43:54.590 --> 43:58.969
These wise women
knew that keeping the house clean

43:59.470 --> 44:01.013
would keep you healthy.

44:01.847 --> 44:04.016
So they cleaned the house with a broom,

44:04.099 --> 44:07.186
and they had cats to get rid of rodents.

44:07.269 --> 44:10.606
There came the time when the Church,

44:11.815 --> 44:13.192
dominated by males,

44:13.859 --> 44:15.653
considered them to be a danger.

44:15.736 --> 44:18.781
So the Church tried to get rid of them.

44:19.865 --> 44:22.076
<i>Demonized during this Papal Inquisition,</i>

44:22.159 --> 44:25.037
<i>Europe's cat population was decimated,</i>

44:26.789 --> 44:30.793
<i>which some believe</i>
<i>may have contributed to the Black Plague.</i>

44:34.713 --> 44:41.679
Black Death, theplague was transmitted
by…rodents, by fleas, actually.

44:42.763 --> 44:45.683
And the fleas were
in the fur of the rodents.

44:47.184 --> 44:50.270
<i> With fewer cats,</i>
<i>the plague was out of control.</i>

44:53.440 --> 44:55.984
<i>Thankfully, even during these dark times,</i>

44:56.068 --> 44:59.697
<i>some people continued to nurture</i>
<i>a bond with cats…</i>

45:10.666 --> 45:14.336
<i>…a relationship</i>
<i>that's still evolving to this day.</i>

45:19.133 --> 45:21.927
There's a history of cats in distilleries.

45:22.678 --> 45:24.972
It's quite a traditional thing
in Scotland.

45:25.472 --> 45:28.767
There was a very famous cat
over at a distillery in Perthshire

45:28.851 --> 45:32.229
called Towser, and he's probably
the most famous distillery cat ever.

45:32.312 --> 45:35.566
-Yeah, he or she is legendary.
-Yeah.

45:35.649 --> 45:38.026
I think he is
the most famous distillery cat.

45:44.658 --> 45:47.119
<i>Five years ago,</i>
<i>Helen and Drew Mckenzie</i>

45:47.202 --> 45:48.829
<i>adopted two working cats</i>

45:49.705 --> 45:51.915
<i>to carry on an age-old tradition.</i>

45:54.877 --> 45:57.504
The abbey was founded in 1191.

45:59.673 --> 46:03.051
We have William Wallace coming here
after his victory over the English

46:03.135 --> 46:04.720
at the Battle of Black Earnside.

46:08.056 --> 46:09.683
So it's got a huge history.

46:10.350 --> 46:12.936
I suppose we're continuing the tradition.

46:13.020 --> 46:15.898
You know, all the cats
that have been here over the years.

46:18.567 --> 46:21.320
<i>They named</i>
<i>the black male Friar John Claw…</i>

46:23.322 --> 46:24.907
<i>and the calico female Vespers,</i>

46:26.366 --> 46:28.827
<i>a nod to the medieval monks</i>
<i>that lived here.</i>

46:29.661 --> 46:34.666
<i>And just like those monks,</i>
<i>these cats begin their services at night.</i>

46:46.428 --> 46:49.681
The eyes of cats are very large
compared to the size of the skull.

46:51.558 --> 46:54.019
They also have something
called the tapetum lucidum,

46:54.102 --> 46:56.855
which is a layer of cells
at the back of the eye

46:56.939 --> 46:59.149
that reflects light back to the retina,

46:59.900 --> 47:03.570
so it allows them
to see very well in low-light conditions.

47:05.239 --> 47:08.242
<i> What they're looking for</i>
<i>poses a very real danger</i>

47:08.325 --> 47:09.952
<i>to the health of the distillery.</i>

47:11.662 --> 47:14.164
Mice are always present
in a distillery

47:14.248 --> 47:18.252
because of the huge amounts of barely,
and grain obviously attracts mice.

47:19.545 --> 47:22.005
Unfortunately,
without getting too technical,

47:22.089 --> 47:25.300
mice kind of wee
all the time, so…

47:25.384 --> 47:28.929
For want of a better expression.
Um, and that's not a good thing.

47:30.347 --> 47:33.767
<i> To find these vermin,</i>
<i>the cats need to get ultrasonic.</i>

47:35.978 --> 47:39.523
The ears of cats
can rotate about 180 degrees.

47:40.566 --> 47:42.693
And they can hear very high frequencies.

47:42.776 --> 47:47.906
This is because the prey that they seek
vocalizes in this auditory range.

47:49.741 --> 47:54.371
So this allows them to kind of localize
and kind of triangulate on prey.

48:08.552 --> 48:10.470
<i> The cats do their job well.</i>

48:13.932 --> 48:18.020
<i>But Helen and Drew were curious</i>
<i>what exactly they were up to.</i>

48:19.938 --> 48:23.483
<i>So Helen put on GPS trackers to find out.</i>

48:26.028 --> 48:28.697
<i>The GPS collars revealed that each night,</i>

48:28.780 --> 48:31.158
<i>Vespers travels more than a mile,</i>

48:31.867 --> 48:34.328
<i>but she never strays too far from home.</i>

48:35.579 --> 48:38.415
Vespers, who is officially
the chief mouser,

48:38.498 --> 48:41.084
is busy getting on with
the day job and night job.

48:42.002 --> 48:44.963
<i>And she's most active just before dawn,</i>

48:45.797 --> 48:47.257
<i>prime rodent time.</i>

48:48.175 --> 48:51.762
Cats are crepuscular animals, okay?

48:52.346 --> 48:55.015
Crespuc-- Crep--
Crepuscular animals

48:55.098 --> 49:00.270
means that they're active
early dawn and at dusk.

49:01.772 --> 49:04.691
<i>Which may explain why cats are so crazy</i>

49:04.775 --> 49:06.276
<i>in the wee hours of the night.</i>

49:08.028 --> 49:11.448
My cats tend to have
the zoomies after we go to bed.

49:14.326 --> 49:17.663
The zoomies, you know,
when cats have a sudden burst of energy.

49:18.705 --> 49:21.708
We call it "FRAP," F-R-A-P.

49:25.587 --> 49:28.674
You can see them, like,
make little chirping noises,

49:28.757 --> 49:31.969
and they get low to the ground,
and they jump from here to there.

49:33.261 --> 49:35.639
They're chasing each other,
they're vocalizing,

49:35.722 --> 49:38.684
just having a grand time
when the rest of us are sleeping.

49:40.727 --> 49:42.187
This is all instinctive behavior.

49:42.270 --> 49:45.065
It goes back to… to the circadian rhythm.

49:45.148 --> 49:49.277
This is an internal clock in our body
that we got from our ancestors.

49:50.320 --> 49:54.408
<i> Some cats have</i>
<i>another peculiar nighttime ritual.</i>

49:55.867 --> 49:59.246
Vespers, in particular,
she is a big present giver.

49:59.746 --> 50:04.459
I reckon Ves probably catches…
four or five things a day.

50:04.543 --> 50:08.547
<i>But why do cats</i>
<i>bring their owners gifts?</i>

50:09.047 --> 50:12.217
We know
that when a mother cat has kittens,

50:12.300 --> 50:15.721
that she will basically bring
the prey back for the kittens,

50:15.804 --> 50:18.932
so they can learn
what kinds of prey are suitable

50:19.016 --> 50:22.102
and kind of let them play with it, uh,

50:22.185 --> 50:26.815
and in kind of a morbid sense,
to get practice trying to get the prey.

50:28.608 --> 50:31.069
<i>Whatever the reason,</i>
<i>it's a compliment.</i>

50:31.695 --> 50:33.363
<i>It means you're family.</i>

50:34.322 --> 50:36.408
And there's few things less pleasant

50:36.491 --> 50:38.994
when you're walking
without slippers on in the morning.

50:41.038 --> 50:43.582
<i> While Vespers performs</i>
<i>the traditional duties,</i>

50:44.541 --> 50:47.878
<i>Friar John Claw has</i>
<i>a more modern approach.</i>

50:48.879 --> 50:50.422
He's very laid-back,

50:51.089 --> 50:53.967
you know, loves the public,
spends a huge amount of time

50:54.051 --> 50:57.220
in the actual visitor center itself
just being stroked.

50:58.096 --> 51:02.017
<i> FJC realized</i>
<i>his sister is all over the mice.</i>

51:02.893 --> 51:04.936
<i>His talents are better used elsewhere.</i>

51:06.521 --> 51:09.775
FJC's role, it could be said,
is more of an ambassador.

51:16.656 --> 51:17.908
He's front of house.

51:17.991 --> 51:21.286
-She's back of house.
-She's back of house, doing the hard work.

51:22.621 --> 51:24.998
<i> Vespers uses instinct.</i>

51:25.082 --> 51:27.918
<i>Friar John Claw uses Instagram.</i>

51:29.461 --> 51:32.839
<i>What started 10,000 years ago</i>
<i>as a working relationship</i>

51:33.965 --> 51:36.259
<i>has evolved into a global obsession.</i>

51:40.555 --> 51:43.391
The way that cats
have gone viral on the Internet is…

51:43.475 --> 51:46.394
I think really exceeds
anything that anyone would have expected.

51:46.478 --> 51:49.940
I believe the second most common reason
people go to the Internet

51:50.023 --> 51:51.358
is to watch cat videos.

51:52.651 --> 51:55.946
<i> Cats are</i>
<i>the number one family-friendly thing</i>

51:56.029 --> 51:57.030
<i>on the Internet…</i>

51:59.116 --> 52:01.618
…<i>with more than 25 billion views.</i>

52:01.701 --> 52:02.536
Oh-ho-ho!

52:03.870 --> 52:05.705
<i> A new study</i>
<i>found that cat videos</i>

52:05.789 --> 52:08.291
<i>actually boost positive emotions</i>

52:08.375 --> 52:10.127
<i>and decrease negative feelings.</i>

52:12.087 --> 52:15.507
<i>In other words,</i>
<i>they provide a big ol' shot of dopamine.</i>

52:17.884 --> 52:20.804
I think that the Internet
has kind of become a space

52:20.887 --> 52:24.474
where cat-lovers can all
kind of unite and just love

52:24.558 --> 52:26.393
cats and laugh at them

52:26.476 --> 52:29.521
and kind of bond over
the silly things that our cats do.

52:29.604 --> 52:31.690
It kind of gives us a space to do that.

52:34.025 --> 52:36.278
<i>Bad behavior makes for a fun video.</i>

52:37.821 --> 52:41.241
<i>But it's not always funny</i>
<i>when it's happening in your own home.</i>

52:43.451 --> 52:46.079
When we have unwanted behavior,

52:46.163 --> 52:49.040
keep in mind that,
you know, cats are being cats.

52:49.124 --> 52:51.459
They don't know you don't want them
on top of your counter.

52:53.170 --> 52:56.047
<i>Rule number one,</i>
<i>never punish a cat.</i>

52:57.757 --> 53:01.011
When your cat is doing
something you don't want,

53:01.094 --> 53:02.429
right, and you punish him,

53:03.054 --> 53:07.100
he sometimes doesn't understand
why you don't like it, right?

53:07.184 --> 53:09.519
It also makes you feel unpredictable.

53:10.979 --> 53:12.814
"All of a sudden,
you're yelling and screaming."

53:12.898 --> 53:14.649
"I don't understand what happened."

53:16.193 --> 53:18.028
<i> The key is positivity.</i>

53:22.657 --> 53:24.910
If your cat is doing
something you don't want,

53:24.993 --> 53:28.955
you wanna be able to distract the cat
and then tell him. Tell him what you want.

53:29.039 --> 53:31.875
"Hey, let's do this.
Come over and touch my hand."

53:31.958 --> 53:35.837
"Go to your bed.
What a smart kitty, yay!"

53:35.921 --> 53:39.007
And your cat goes,
"Yeah, I'm the best cat ever!"

53:41.968 --> 53:45.889
<i> For really bad habits,</i>
<i>classical conditioning is not enough.</i>

53:47.599 --> 53:53.104
Counterconditioning is the process
of changing an emotional response.

53:54.314 --> 53:57.359
<i>This is when you pull out the good stuff,</i>

53:57.442 --> 54:00.111
<i>their favorite, most irresistible treat.</i>

54:00.779 --> 54:04.199
Offering something
so highly valuable or rewarding

54:04.282 --> 54:08.411
that the animal goes,
"Oh! That wasn't so bad. I like this."

54:09.746 --> 54:11.706
I always give the example to my clients

54:11.790 --> 54:14.501
of, what if every time
you walked out of the house,

54:14.584 --> 54:17.921
you had a snarky neighbor,
and he always said something mean to you?

54:18.421 --> 54:20.966
So you try to avoid going out
when he's out there.

54:22.259 --> 54:25.553
But what if every time
you went out there, I gave you $1,000?

54:25.637 --> 54:26.763
Huh?

54:27.681 --> 54:31.059
Then you're like, "That's not so bad.
I don't mind seeing that guy."

54:31.977 --> 54:34.312
What if you saw him four times a day,
and you got $4,000?

54:34.396 --> 54:36.898
You're gonna be like, "Yeah! Bring it on!"

54:36.982 --> 54:39.818
"Where is he?" You're gonna wanna see
that guy all the time, right?

54:41.111 --> 54:43.238
So that's what counterconditioning is.

54:43.321 --> 54:45.240
You can change a situation

54:45.323 --> 54:50.120
from being negative,
to more neutral, to then positive.

54:52.747 --> 54:56.001
<i> Like any relationship,</i>
<i>it can take patience,</i>

54:56.626 --> 54:58.253
<i>but it's worth it.</i>

54:59.337 --> 55:02.799
You get the sense sometimes
that they might not need you,

55:03.967 --> 55:05.552
but they still want you.

55:05.635 --> 55:10.598
And that's this very unique and mystical
and deep-seated relationship.

55:11.182 --> 55:13.184
<i>A cat's true motivation</i>

55:13.268 --> 55:16.521
<i>isn't as easy to interpret</i>
<i>as some other pets'.</i>

55:17.939 --> 55:21.234
Dogs see
their owners as gods.

55:22.610 --> 55:24.487
But cats think of <i>themselves </i>as gods.

55:26.031 --> 55:27.866
Cats don't want to do
what they don't like.

55:28.533 --> 55:30.577
They want to sleep
when they want to sleep,

55:30.660 --> 55:33.121
eat when they want to eat,
play when they want to play.

55:36.750 --> 55:40.045
<i> Don't mistake</i>
<i>independence for indifference.</i>

55:40.754 --> 55:44.090
If you kind of have that perception
that cats are aloof,

55:44.174 --> 55:46.259
they don't care about social interaction,

55:46.343 --> 55:48.428
so you don't go out of your way
to interact with them,

55:49.012 --> 55:52.307
you're basically shaping
the cat to then also be aloof

55:52.390 --> 55:54.559
because that was what
you expected of them.

55:55.602 --> 55:57.812
In our work, we found that

55:57.896 --> 56:01.441
how the person behaves
really does impact the cat's behavior.

56:02.817 --> 56:05.904
<i>Kristyn's research is proving</i>
<i>how a cat treats you</i>

56:06.488 --> 56:09.449
<i>directly reflects how you treat them.</i>

56:10.992 --> 56:15.580
<i>One step further, her work is showing</i>
<i>they might even pick up on how we feel.</i>

56:18.166 --> 56:21.294
So this is known as
the social-referencing test.

56:21.378 --> 56:24.422
And the whole idea is
that this fan with streamers

56:24.506 --> 56:26.466
is totally novel to the cat.

56:26.549 --> 56:30.053
So he doesn't know if it's something scary
or if it's something fun.

56:30.553 --> 56:34.140
So the whole idea is that the person
can put off emotional cues

56:34.224 --> 56:36.226
and see how the cat responds.

56:36.976 --> 56:38.603
Carl, that's scary!

56:39.646 --> 56:41.689
Carl, that's scary, isn't it?

56:42.482 --> 56:43.983
Oh no!

56:44.067 --> 56:46.820
Oh no! Oh my gosh!

56:47.695 --> 56:48.780
Look at that!

56:48.863 --> 56:51.241
<i>When Kristyn acts scared of the fan,</i>

56:51.324 --> 56:52.742
<i>Carl tries to hide.</i>

56:55.703 --> 56:57.414
Is the fan scary?

56:58.164 --> 57:00.750
<i>A quick reset</i>
<i>and an attitude adjustment,</i>

57:00.834 --> 57:02.419
<i>and it's time for round two.</i>

57:06.464 --> 57:08.550
So if I'm happy towards the fan,

57:08.633 --> 57:11.719
we should see if the cat
can pick up on my emotions.

57:16.850 --> 57:19.811
Look. Look at what a nice fan.

57:21.354 --> 57:23.231
Look at what a good fan.

57:23.314 --> 57:27.026
<i> When she speaks nicely</i>
<i>to the fan and is not scared,</i>

57:27.110 --> 57:28.903
<i>Carl seems more confident.</i>

57:29.654 --> 57:31.656
Look at those streamers.

57:33.116 --> 57:34.200
Look.

57:35.076 --> 57:37.495
<i> The fan is no longer a threat.</i>

57:38.246 --> 57:39.330
No more fear!

57:43.126 --> 57:44.461
<i> It's not just Carl.</i>

57:45.962 --> 57:50.258
<i>Seventy-nine percent of cats</i>
<i>look to their owners for emotional advice.</i>

57:51.926 --> 57:54.387
<i>For scientists, it's another breakthrough.</i>

57:57.307 --> 58:01.019
<i>It seems cats</i>
<i>are experts at feeling our feelings…</i>

58:03.730 --> 58:05.356
<i>good and bad.</i>

58:06.858 --> 58:10.320
If you even have a bad mood
and you go into training cats,

58:10.403 --> 58:11.738
just walk away.

58:11.821 --> 58:13.823
Do not go… Do not go there.

58:13.907 --> 58:17.535
They feel everything,
and they make it worse.

58:18.077 --> 58:19.245
Asia, come here.

58:22.707 --> 58:26.669
<i> Cats have learned to be empaths</i>
<i>to adapt and survive.</i>

58:28.254 --> 58:30.965
There is an evolutionary advantage

58:31.049 --> 58:34.761
to being able to look at social partners
in your environment

58:34.844 --> 58:36.596
and gather information.

58:36.679 --> 58:40.183
So if you're unable to read
anybody's response,

58:40.266 --> 58:43.061
then you have really cut yourself off

58:43.144 --> 58:46.981
from a whole lot of information
about how to react

58:47.065 --> 58:49.108
to something potentially dangerous.

58:50.318 --> 58:53.655
<i> This revelation</i>
<i>that cats pick up on our feelings</i>

58:53.738 --> 58:57.242
<i>then took a much bigger turn</i>
<i>than anyone ever expected.</i>

59:01.538 --> 59:04.916
<i>Back in Japan,</i>
<i>Dr. Saho Takagi noticed something.</i>

59:07.669 --> 59:11.589
I realized
that we can observe different behaviors

59:11.673 --> 59:15.343
in cats in the US and the ones in Japan.

59:17.971 --> 59:22.308
In Japan, cats have a hard time
with unfamiliar places.

59:23.851 --> 59:25.645
However, cats I saw in the US…

59:28.648 --> 59:34.237
…act normal even in unfamiliar places.

59:34.320 --> 59:41.244
So Japanese and American cats
might have different personalities.

59:42.245 --> 59:45.498
<i> Kristyn and Saho</i>
<i>decided to run the same experiments</i>

59:45.582 --> 59:47.584
<i>in the US and in Japan.</i>

59:49.460 --> 59:52.505
<i>And they're finding</i>
<i>the cats are different.</i>

59:56.050 --> 59:59.387
We're seeing social differences
between cats in Japan and the US.

1:00:00.680 --> 1:00:07.312
I realized
that our cultural differences affect cats.

1:00:09.689 --> 1:00:12.775
<i>Is human culture changing cat culture?</i>

1:00:14.193 --> 1:00:17.614
Japan is an island nation.

1:00:18.823 --> 1:00:23.119
Most cat owners keep
their cats completely indoors.

1:00:23.202 --> 1:00:27.123
People in Japan
rarely have a party at home.

1:00:27.957 --> 1:00:30.835
Therefore, for cats in Japan,
the frequency of meeting strangers

1:00:30.918 --> 1:00:33.838
is much less than for cats in the US.

1:00:34.756 --> 1:00:39.385
These might be factors contributing
to the differences between cats in Japan

1:00:39.469 --> 1:00:41.471
and cats in the US.

1:00:43.556 --> 1:00:46.601
<i> Their research</i>
<i>suggests these cultural differences</i>

1:00:46.684 --> 1:00:50.355
<i>might actually be handed down</i>
<i>from generation to generation.</i>

1:00:53.941 --> 1:00:58.404
<i>And in one culture, it's bringing</i>
<i>our species even closer together.</i>

1:01:11.876 --> 1:01:14.504
<i>Even before Istanbul was Constantinople,</i>

1:01:14.587 --> 1:01:17.090
<i>it was the city of cats.</i>

1:01:18.966 --> 1:01:23.846
<i>These streets are home</i>
<i>to more than 100,000 community cats</i>

1:01:23.930 --> 1:01:26.724
<i>perfectly suited to an urban lifestyle.</i>

1:01:31.771 --> 1:01:35.358
Nowadays, when you go to Istanbul,
you find these cats around.

1:01:36.943 --> 1:01:40.530
They are cats
that belong to the neighborhood.

1:01:41.280 --> 1:01:43.658
They are not owned by a specific person.

1:01:44.450 --> 1:01:48.204
People provide the infrastructure for cats

1:01:48.287 --> 1:01:50.248
so that they can survive,

1:01:50.331 --> 1:01:54.252
but they are not… They do not belong
to somebody specifically.

1:01:56.379 --> 1:02:02.093
<i> In 2021, Istanbul introduced</i>
<i>new laws protecting these cats,</i>

1:02:02.176 --> 1:02:05.221
<i>some of the most progressive legislation</i>
<i>in the world.</i>

1:02:07.348 --> 1:02:11.644
<i>Treating a cat as an equal</i>
<i>and seeing things from their point of view</i>

1:02:11.728 --> 1:02:14.564
<i>is the best way</i>
<i>to strengthen the relationship.</i>

1:02:15.857 --> 1:02:16.691
Hi.

1:02:25.283 --> 1:02:27.452
The whole reason
my specialty exists

1:02:27.535 --> 1:02:30.955
is because people recognize
they have this deep bond with this animal,

1:02:31.038 --> 1:02:32.290
this deep love.

1:02:34.292 --> 1:02:36.002
We do it for the love of animals.

1:02:36.627 --> 1:02:39.213
We do it because we recognize
the human-animal bond.

1:02:40.882 --> 1:02:43.718
And I don't know why I'm crying.
Stop making me cry.

1:02:43.801 --> 1:02:47.805
Um… yeah, this is why we do it,
because we love animals.

1:02:49.932 --> 1:02:52.810
<i> It's clear we love cats.</i>

1:02:53.853 --> 1:02:56.773
<i>Which leads us</i>
<i>to the biggest cat question of all.</i>

1:02:59.233 --> 1:03:01.694
Do I think cats love us?

1:03:02.737 --> 1:03:05.656
It's really hard to measure
emotions in cats,

1:03:05.740 --> 1:03:07.909
but I do feel like,
based on their behavior,

1:03:07.992 --> 1:03:09.827
based on their relationship,

1:03:09.911 --> 1:03:15.374
that cats can form such a deep bond
with someone that it is akin to love.

1:03:19.962 --> 1:03:22.715
Cats love their owners very much.

1:03:22.799 --> 1:03:28.679
I believe that my cats definitely love me.

1:03:30.389 --> 1:03:32.850
It's pretty clear
that cats provide

1:03:33.476 --> 1:03:37.313
emotional support,
a feeling of wellness, happiness.

1:03:37.939 --> 1:03:42.860
This notion that you can come home
and have unconditional love from your cat

1:03:42.944 --> 1:03:44.821
is something that's vital.

1:03:50.576 --> 1:03:52.495
<i>With all the devotion of her family,</i>

1:03:52.578 --> 1:03:56.415
<i>Eddy is perfectly positioned</i>
<i>to become the next big superstar.</i>

1:03:59.585 --> 1:04:03.089
<i> All she needs to do</i>
<i>is complete the paper hoop.</i>

1:04:08.845 --> 1:04:12.598
<i>We're only beginning</i>
<i>to realize the potential of cats.</i>

1:04:13.224 --> 1:04:17.812
There is still so much
we don't know about cats.

1:04:17.895 --> 1:04:21.107
The future will bring
more discoveries bit by bit.

1:04:23.150 --> 1:04:24.694
<i> The more we learn,</i>

1:04:24.777 --> 1:04:28.239
<i>the more we realize</i>
<i>just how deep our connection is.</i>

1:04:30.867 --> 1:04:33.786
They feel the love
that you giving to them.

1:04:33.870 --> 1:04:37.290
And they are kind of, like, feeding on it.

1:04:39.000 --> 1:04:40.710
Love is going both ways.

1:04:42.837 --> 1:04:46.340
<i> If we can learn</i>
<i>how to bring out the best in our felines,</i>

1:04:46.424 --> 1:04:48.801
<i>they will bring out the best in us.</i>

1:04:50.803 --> 1:04:53.598
I can't imagine my life without cats.

1:04:54.265 --> 1:04:57.393
They are my animals. I feel them.

1:04:57.476 --> 1:05:00.980
And I hope they love me
as much as I love them.

1:05:02.398 --> 1:05:04.525
<i>When everything comes together,</i>

1:05:04.609 --> 1:05:07.153
<i>the results can be magical.</i>
